    <item>
      <title>The Year in Review:  Music</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=OT&amp;message.id=164922#M164922</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;Ah, here it is, the year is ending and I am thinking back about what I've done, and things that I still remember.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Last year I was listening to the Counting Crows (again)&amp;nbsp;and for the first time believing that "It's been a long December/but there's reason to believe/maybe this year will be better than the last" and it was.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I decided that I would try and buy a new CD every payday, didn't quite make it but I did get a lot.&amp;nbsp; However, for me musically 2006 was the Year of the Greatest Hits of the 70s.&amp;nbsp; A lot of what I bought was updating my old vinyl to CD format.&amp;nbsp; Since I still have my albums and can still play them, I didn't buy 6-7 albums by the same artist and just got a greatest hits collection instead.&amp;nbsp; If I remember all of them, here's what I got (in no particular order):&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Van Morrison, Cat Stevens, John Denver, Gordon Lightfoot, Bonnie Tyler, The Cars, Jim Croce, REM, and I don't remember if I got it this year or last, but I did listen to Lenny Kravitz a lot this past summer.&amp;nbsp; I also had to rebuy Tom Petty's Greatest Hits to replace my missing copy.&amp;nbsp; While I will get a greatest hits compilation, I decided that mostly I wanted Gerry Rafferty's City to City (the one with Baker Street, still probably one of the most recognized sax lines of all time) so that's what I got.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I did buy a number of non-greatest hits albums.&amp;nbsp; Weird Al, of course.&amp;nbsp; Snow Patrol which I've listened to a lot.&amp;nbsp; I did finally break down and get the U2 Atom Bomb CD last month and now they come out with their own Greatest Hits...&amp;nbsp; I bought a couple of albums where mostly I liked one song.&amp;nbsp; Notably (or infamously perhaps) was Aqualung, while I really liked Brighter than Sunshine, the rest of the album puts me to sleep.&amp;nbsp; I just picked up Soul Asylum with Stand Up (and be proud).&amp;nbsp; I think I'm forgetting a couple of albums so apparently they weren't very notable.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I've liked some of the things my son introduced me to.&amp;nbsp; There was one group particularly that is not signed with a label so far as I know but sells their CDs at their shows that I really like.&amp;nbsp; I'll try to remember to ask him what their name was again.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;My radio station put on some new artists, of those that stick in my head are Death Cab for Cutie and the Decemberists.&amp;nbsp; They also play a lot of Los Lonely Boys -- which doesn't segue well with either of the two previous groups.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I think the next album I'll be buying is the latest Tom Petty.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;That's my year in review...&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; what's yours and what should I give a listen to.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Tue, 12 Dec 2006 13:03:48 GMT</pubDate>
